text.tspan: Hello Canada! Countries around the world educate young children to code
for future excellence, but in 2013 there was no national movement in
Canada.
Why early education? So we can engage girls before gender ste
reotypes set in and learning to code is like learning a new language - it’s
easier to learn when we start young! Also, 84% of Canadian primary school
teachers are women and few of them know how to code. If we want to give
all children the head start they need for future success, supporting teach
ers in the classroom is a priority.
We register as a national not-for-profit
dedicated to bringing code to Canadian children’s early education.
SUMMER
FALL
We knock on Montreal primary school doors -they open!- to start working with
teachers to bring code into classrooms. We talk with corporate leaders, uni
versity professors and send LOTS of letters to provincial and federal leaders.
Our first grant from CIRA helps us develop classroom materials for
Canadian teachers. We host our first Education Committee meeting,
made up of primary school teachers, university professors, computer
scientists & programmers.
SPRING
FALL
And to follow the grant, our first sponsor! Thanks to Vigilant Global for asking
“How can we help you?”and covering (4 years in a row!) office rent at Notman
House and supporting our national growth. We also begin our first year
mentoring teams of girls at Technovation, a global technology
entrepreneurship competition.
We bring Code Club to Canada. With clubs around the world and a 48% girl
attendance rate, it’s a perfect fit for our mission to increase opportunities for
girls. With materials available in 20 languages, it’s ideal for all Canadian
kids.
SPRING
FALL
We partner with organizations like Hour of Code and CBC Kids to reach
Canadians from coast to coast to coast; and branch out outside of Quebec
with to support teachers and kids in British Columbia.
Teacher training workshops enter pilot mode in Montreal and Quebec City,
and soon after, Vancouver and Toronto. We also roll out our first Code,
Create, Play workshops, which introduce gaming, story-telling, art &
hardware, with code.
SPRING
FALL
In partnership with Lighthouse labs, Kids Code Jeunesse wins a contract to
work with the Ministry of Education in British Columbia, to help integrate
coding into the new curriculum.
Kids Code Jeunesse receives federal NSERC funding for 3 years to expand
operations across Canada. We are also the only Canadian organization to
win a Google Rise 2017 grant to support national growth of Code, Create,
Play workshops.
SPRING
Going into our 5th school year, we’re excited to work with teachers and
children in schools in BC, Alberta, Ontario, and Quebec. And in every
province and territory with our Code Clubs!
FALL
